SIMPLE: wharf
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wharf
<hw>Wharf</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Wharfs</plw> <pr>(#)</pr> or <plw>Wharves</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu>
<ety>[AS. <ets>hwerf</ets>, <ets>hwearf</ets>, a returning, a change,
from <ets>hweorfan</ets> to turn, turn about, go about; akin to D.
<ets>werf</ets> a wharf, G. <ets>werft</ets>, Sw. <ets>varf</ets> a
shipbuilder's yard, Dan. <ets>verft</ets> wharf, dockyard, G.
<ets>werben</ets> to enlist, to engage, woo, OHG. <ets>werban</ets> to
turn about, go about, be active or occupied, Icel. <ets>hverfa</ets> to
turn, Goth. <ets>hwa⟦iacute⟧rban</ets>, <ets>hwarb⟦omac⟧n</ets>, to
walk. Cf. <er>Whirl</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A structure or platform of timber, masonry, iron,
earth, or other material, built on the shore of a harbor, river, canal,
or the like, and usually extending from the shore to deep water, so that
vessels may lie close alongside to receive and discharge cargo,
passengers, etc.; a quay; a pier.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Commerce pushes its <qex>wharves</qex> into the sea.</q>
<rj><qau>Bancroft.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Out upon the <qex>wharfs</qex> they came,⟦br⟧
Knight and burgher, lord and dame.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The plural of this word is generally written
<xex>wharves</xex> in the United States, and <xex>wharfs</xex> in
England; but many recent English writers use
<xex>wharves</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <ety>[AS. <ets>hwearf</ets>.]</ety> <def>The bank of a
river, or the shore of the sea.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧The fat
weed that roots itself in ease on Lethe <xex>wharf</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Wharf boat</b></col>, <cd>a kind of boat moored at the
bank of a river, and used for a wharf, in places where the height of the
water is so variable that a fixed wharf would be useless.</cd> <mark>[U.
S.]</mark> <au>Bartlett.</au> -- <col><b>Wharf rat</b></col>.
<fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>The common brown rat.</cd>
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>A neglected boy who lives around the wharfs.</cd>
<mark>[Slang]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1643 -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wharf</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Wharf
<hw>Wharf</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Wharfed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Wharfing</conjf>.]</vmorph>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To guard or secure by a firm wall of timber or stone
constructed like a wharf; to furnish with a wharf or wharfs.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To place upon a wharf; to bring to a
wharf.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wharfage</ent>⟦br⟧
